<div1 type="trialAccount" id="t18500610-1221">
               <interp inst="t18500610-1221" type="uri" value="sessionsPapers/18500610"></interp>
               <interp inst="t18500610-1221" type="date" value="18500610"></interp>
               <join result="criminalCharge" id="t18500610-1221-charge-1" targOrder="Y" targets="def1-1221-18500610 t18500610-1221-offence-1 t18500610-1221-verdict-1"></join>
               <p>1221. <persName id="def1-1221-18500610" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def1-1221-18500610" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-1221-18500610" type="surname" value="TUCKER"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-1221-18500610" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">WILLIAM TUCKER</hi>
                  </persName>
                  <rs id="t18500610-1221-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18500610-1221-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18500610-1221-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="simpleLarceny"></interp>, stealing 1,765lbs. weight of leather, value 60<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.; the goods of <persName id="t18500610-name-990" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18500610-name-990" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18500610-name-990" type="surname" value="BOUTCHER"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18500610-name-990" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18500610-1221-offence-1 t18500610-name-990"></join>William Boutcher</persName> and others.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. CLARKSON</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">conducted the Prosecution.</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18500610-name-991" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18500610-name-991" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18500610-name-991" type="surname" value="WILKS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18500610-name-991" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>JAMBS WILKS</persName>
                  </hi>. I am warehouseman to Mr. William Boucher and two others. On Monday, 31st Dec, about three o'clock in the afternoon, the prisoner came to their warehouse at Bermondsey—he asked to see some low-priced butts of leather—I showed him two parcels—he selected some, which amounted to 59<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. odd—he said, "You will send them in to-morrow morning, and send the invoice with them"—I said, "Yes, but I am not the master; I must have the cash for them on delivery of the goods"—he said, "Well, send them before nine o'clock in the morning; I shall be sure to be at home, and I will give the man the money"—I had sold him a small parcel of goods on the Friday before—that was for cash—it was the first time I had sold to him—after he was gone, I had the leather weighed—next morning I saw the leather loaded, and gave the invoice to Saxby—I told him to be sure to bring back the goods or the money—he left the yard with the goods at a little before eight o'clock, and returned a little after nine without the goods—(I suppose the distance from our place was about a mile and a half)—in consequence of what I heard from him, and by the direction of Mr. Vicary, I went with Saxby and the horse and cart, about eleven o'clock the same morning, to the prisoner's house—I knocked at the front-door, and spoke to a female—in consequence of what she said, I went round to the yard-door, knocked, but no one came—I waited about five minutes—I left Saxby there, and I went round again to the house-door—I knocked twice, and the door was opened by a female—I went in and went through the house into the warehouse—I saw the leather there—one of the parcels contained thirteen bales, of five butts each—I took up one of the bales, and opened the back-gate, and gave the bale to Saxby, who put it into the cart—I went back and attempted to get another bale, but the men in the yard locked the yard-gates; locked the warehouse-door, and locked me in and leather and all—I called to Saxby, who was outside, to come round to the house-door—he came into the house, and I came out and left him in charge—I went back to my employer, and communicated what had happened to Mr. Vicary—it was then about half-past eleven o'clock—I went back to the prisoner's house, and was let in at the front-door by the same female—I waited from half-past four till five—I then saw the prisoner—I asked him why he did not give the man the money as he promised—he said he had been disappointed of some money, and he could not—I said, "Well, then, I must have the goods"—he said that I should neither have goods nor money—I then sent Saxby to my employers, and after some more conversation with the prisoner, on the return of Saxby I sent for a policeman—the policeman said he did not know what it was, whether it was false pretences or a debt, and he could not detain the prisoner—at last, when I found I could not get the policeman to take him, I left—the prisoner told me I might stop as long as I liked, he should neither give me goods nor</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="185006100182"></xptr>
               <p>money—this was on Tuesday—I went again on Wednesday, and went through into the warehouse—the leather was then gone—they said the prisoner was gone out—I went again on Thursday, and they said he was ill in bed—I went again on Friday—they said he was out of town, and would be home on Saturday, and they had not heard anything of him.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18500610-name-992" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18500610-name-992" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18500610-name-992" type="surname" value="SAXBY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18500610-name-992" type="given" value="WALTER"></interp>WALTER SAXBY</persName>
                  </hi>. On Monday, 31st Dec, I assisted Mr. Wilks in weigh<lb></lb>ing the bales of leather—there were thirteen bales of light butts, and three bales of heavy butts—Mr. Wilks took the weights down—these are the cor<lb></lb>rect weights he took down—next morning I went with my master's cart to the prisoner's house in Ann's-place, about eight o'clock—I knocked at the door—a man opened it—I told him I had brought the bales of leather from Boutcher and Co.—he told me to drive round to the back gates—I drove round, and the gates were open—I stopped my cart outside the gates, and two men who were there told me to bring the goods in—I said I could not bring them in till I saw Mr. Tucker—the cart was outside, and I waited in<lb></lb>side—Mr Tucker came in a little while—I showed him the invoice, and told him I had brought the goods, and 1 was to have the money for them; I could not leave them without—I put the invoice into his hand—I never received it back again—he said, "Very well, that is all right, put them down here"—that was inside the gates—I put the goods down, and he said, "They must be weighed"—I assisted in weighing them—he put down the weights on a slate—he did not let me see it, he took it in-doorts, and told me to drive round to the front—I drove round to the front, and the prisoner came to the front and asked me if I should like to have a pint of beer, or a glass of gin, it being a cold morning—I said yes, and he gave me sixpence—that had not the effect of getting me away from the door—I was at the door outside—he shut the door, and said he should be ready for me in a minute or two—in two or three minutes he opened the door, and said there was 21bs. short weight—I believe that would make a difference of 1<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 4<hi rend="italic">d</hi>.—I told him I knew nothing about the weight, my orders were to bring the money back, and I must have it or the goods—I said our scales were very correct, and his might make that dif<lb></lb>ference—he said, "Oh, my good man, don't be alarmed, I will go with you in the cart and settle with Mr. Wilks"—that threw me off my guard—he went and got his hat, and got in the cart, and went with me—when we got to the Swan, the prisoner said, "Which way are you going? I am going this way," pointing down Swan-street, which leads to the Grange-road—as soon as he said that he jumped out of the cart over the front—I asked him why he did not come to settle with my master, and I whipped the horse to prevent his getting out, but he got out and went down Swan-street—I went after him, and overtook him about 200 yards off—I asked him why he did not come with me and settle with Mr. Wilks—he turned round and told me not to insult him—I told him I did not insult him, all I wanted was for him to come and settle with Mr. Wilks as he promised—I followed him down as far as the Grange-road, and then be said he would come and settle with Mr. Wilks in an hour—he went on, and I went and told Mr. Wilks—it was then a little past nine—I went to ray breakfast, and on my return, by direction of one of the partners, Mr. Wilks and I took the horse and cart and went to the pri<lb></lb>soner's—we tried to get the leather—we got one bundle, containing five butts, and then were told we should neither have money nor leather, and we came home without money or goods.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. COCKLE</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> When he got out of the cart did he not tell you he was going to cull on Mr. Edwards, who had disappointed him of a 53<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. bill? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No.</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="185006100183"></xptr>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. COCKLE</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">to</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. WILKS</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Although the prisoner had only dealt with you once before, yet you knew previously that he was in the same business? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes; I had known him as having been in that business about six months—the amount of the order he gave on 31st Dec, was 59<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 6<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.—the preceding order was 16<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. odd—I believe he paid that in cash in the counting-house—when he said, "Send the invoice with them, "I said, "I am not the master, the goods must be paid for on delivery"—I had no master there at that time—it was a regulation of my own—I had no authority to sell to strangers, except on cash, without my master being there—I had no discretion—I believe 50 pounds of this was recovered from Mr. Welter—the prisoner did not say that he had been disappointed by a Mr. Edwards, who owed him 53<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. on a bill of exchange—on 1st Jan., I charged the prisoner with having committed a crime, I sent for the policeman, and be refused to take him in charge.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Did you not say to the prisoner, in the presence of the policeman, after some altercation about this, "Very well, mind, I will take care yon shall have the handle of leather which we took this morning sent back to you, and then if you don't pay on Saturday you will have a writ?" <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No; the prisoner lent out for some gin, and made two glasses of gin-and-water, one for him<lb></lb>self and one for me, but I never touched it—the policeman drank the glass that was made for me—the goods were sent on Tuesday 1st Jan.—I went on the day after—I did not find the prisoner there—I did not see Mr. Weller there any time during that week—I went about eight o'clock each morning—the prisoner was not taken on this charge; he was in Whitecross-street prison for debt before we could find him.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18500610-name-993" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18500610-name-993" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18500610-name-993" type="surname" value="WILKS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18500610-name-993" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>JAMES WILKS</persName>
                  </hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">re-examined. Q.</hi> Did the prisoner come and pay for the first parcel of goods? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> He did, in the afternoon—the foreman said when the goods went, that Mr. Tucker was gone to our house to pay for them.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Witnesses for the Defence.</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18500610-name-994" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18500610-name-994" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18500610-name-994" type="surname" value="LITTLE"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18500610-name-994" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>WILLIAM LITTLE</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">policeman, M</hi> 118). On Tuesday afternoon, 1st. Jan., I was on duty near the prisoner's house, and was called in about five o'clock—I found the prisoner, the carman, and the prosecutor's foreman—he wanted to give the prisoner in charge, but be seemed to hesitate, first saying he would, and then he would not, saying he wished to have it settled some other way, he wished to come to an arrangement—the prisoner said lie had been disap<lb></lb>pointed, and he should be able to settle the bill on the Saturday following, provided the bundle of leather was returned back which was taken away in the morning—that was agreed to by the prosecutor's foreman, and they shook hands—the foreman replied that he would send the leather back on the morrow morning, and if the whole amount was not paid on the Saturday morning, he should serve him with a writ—the words the foreman said were, "Very good, it shall be done, the leather shall be returned," and if not paid for on Saturday, he should serve him with a writ—after this agreement had been come to, they took some gin-and-water together, and the prosecutor's foreman left the house—they parted in a friendly manner.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. CLARKSON</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> I am afraid you have forgotten part; you have not said that you took any gin-and-water? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No, I did not—I swear that I partook of no gin-and-watch—I was sent for to take this man into custody—Mr. Wilks did not complain that the man had got his master's goods, which he agreed to pay for or return them, and he could neither get goods nor money.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Then what reason did he give for sending for you? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> He wanted to charge him with obtaining goods under false pretences.</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="185006100184"></xptr>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. CLARKSON</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Did you tell him yon could not take him on that charge? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No; I was willing to take him, but he seemed to hesitate about charging him—the carman fetched me, I do not know his name—he told me to come to Ann's-place to take a man into custody—he said his master wanted to charge a man; I asked what for, and he said he did not know—I swear he said that—I went with him, and waited there a few moments—there was some conversation—the foreman first said he would charge him, and then he said he would not—I said, If you charge him, you take the responsibility on yourself"—he said he wished to have it settled some other way, he wished to have his money—they had some conversation about the goods—I did not hear exactly what they said—upon my solemn oath I took no gin-and-water.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. COCKLE</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Is it a regulation that when on duty you are not to drink? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes, we are allowed to drink half-a-pint of beer in the presence of a sergeant.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18500610-name-995" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18500610-name-995" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18500610-name-995" type="surname" value="THOMAS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18500610-name-995" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>THOMAS THOMAS</persName>
                  </hi>. I am an agent, and live at 4, Ely-court, Hatton-garden. I went to the prisoner's house on Tuesday, 1st Jan.—I was admitted through the private house, and was put into his counting-house to wait for him—he was in the house, but was engaged—this was between five and six o'clock—I was able to see from the counting-house into the parlour—there is a slight partition and a glass door—Mr. Tucker was in the parlour, and there other persons; one of them was a policeman, I do not know that I should recog<lb></lb>nize him—I should say that this is the man(<hi rend="italic">Little</hi>)—I heard some conver<lb></lb>sation, and I heard some person say, "Remember, if you do not pay the money on Saturday, you will have a writ"—I then saw two persons leave—I know Mr. Edwards; I know the prisoner had a bill on him.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> What about the bill? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I met Mr. Edwards that morning, and at his request I went to the prisoner about it—I am a commer<lb></lb>cial agent—I have no office—I have no place of business—I do not practise on 'Change—I am a general agent—I have lived at 4, Ely-court, a few weeks—I merely occupy the bedroom there on the ground-floor—I never saw the prisoner till 1st January—about three weeks afterwards I had to go to Whitecross-street prison and I saw him there—I have lived three weeks where I do now—I lived before that at Camden-town—I was coming to town every day—I have the use of part of an office at Mr. Jones's, a wine-merchant, 58, Greek-street, Soho—I am allowed to have my letters addressed there, and to come and write my letters there—before I went to Camden<lb></lb>town I think I lived (upon my word, I almost forget) at 2, Pemberton-row, Gough-square—before that at 21, Tottenham-court, New-road—I was in a situation there, at a wine-merchant's, twelve months.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">to</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">WALTER SAXBY</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Did you see who drank the gin-and-water? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I saw the policeman in the passage—he drank out of it—I saw biro drink it—I was in the passage.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner.</hi> The goods were not parted with on the Wednesday.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">to</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">JAMES WILKS</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> When were the goods gone? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> They were gone on the Wednesday morning by eight o'clock.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner.</hi> They were not away till five in the afternoon.</p>
